<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1440,514,575]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,514,540]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[566,646,514,540]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelosa">
<emphasis box="[566,646,514,540]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">adelosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Greek adjective that stems from 
<emphasis box="[1077,1145,514,540]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">adelos</emphasis>
(= obscure). I refer to the dimly visible light brown markings on the elytral disc.
</paragraph>
